Package edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic

Class Effect

java.lang.Object
edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic.Assignment
edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic.Effect
All Implemented Interfaces:
Atom, Expression, Logical, Proposition, Simplifiable, Typed, Serializable, Comparable<Logical>
public class Effect extends Assignment implements Atom
An effect is an atomic assignment that must have a fluent on the left side, a valued expression on the right side, and a condition in in disjunctive normal form under which the assignment would occur.
Author:
Stephen G. Ware

    • toEffect

      public Clause<Effect> toEffect()
      Description copied from interface: Expression
      Converts an expression whose type is boolean to disjunctive normal form (DNF) suitable to appear in the deterministic effect of an event. Because effects must be deterministic, this process must result in a disjunction of no more than one conjunctive clause whose atoms are effects. Because there will only be at most one clause, that clause is returned instead of a disjunction. If no clauses would be returned (in other words, if false would be returned), the null clause is returned.
      Specified by:
      toEffect in interface Expression
      Overrides:
      toEffect in class Assignment
      Returns:
      a conjunctive clause whose atoms are effects

    • combine

      public Effect combine(Atom other)
      Description copied from interface: Atom
      If a conjunction of this atom and a given atom can be simplified to a single atom, this method returns that atom; if not, null is returned. If this method returns null, it does not mean the atoms are contradictory (see Atom.negates(Atom)), only that they cannot be combined into a single atom.
      Specified by:
      combine in interface Atom
      Parameters:
      other - the other atom which can possibly be combined with this one
      Returns:
      a single atom which expresses both this atom and the given atom, or null if no such atom exists
